Lastly, the several translations of the Bible, set forth at these times with special Prefaces before them, made as well by Santes Pagninus the Dominican at Lyons, by Antonius Bruciolus in Italy, and by the author of Birk- man's edition at Antwerp, as by Robert Stephen in the edition of Vatablus at Paris‚—every one declaring the dis- tinction, that was then commonly known and received, be- tween the canonical and the apocryphal books of Scripture, —all these (being joined with the former authors whom we have produced in all ages) are most evident and sufficient witnesses, that neither we in the Church of England, nor the protestant Churches abroacl, have herein transgressed those bounds, which the Propliets, and Apostles, and generally all our forefathers in the Faith, had set out and prescribed for us.
